Photo by Raphael Nogueira on UnsplashA lot of developers have had this moment in Vue:
<template>
<button @click="handleClick">Click me</button>
</template>
<script setup>
function handleClick() {
return false
}
</script>You return false inside the handler, expecting Vue to prevent the default behavior, just like it does in plain HTML with onclick. But nothing happens. The form still submits, the link still navigates, the event still bubbles.
This behavior surprises people, but it is not a bug. It is a consequence of how Vue attaches event handlers under the hood. Once you understand the difference between legacy on* handlers and modern addEventListener, the design makes sense. That is what this post is about.
How This Discussion Started
This post started because I was staring at some keyboard navigation code in useCardGridKeyboardNav.js and kept running into empty return statements:
const handleGridKeydown = (event) => {
if (!NAV_KEYS.has(event.key)) return
const container = event.currentTarget
if (!container) return
const items = Array.from(container.querySelectorAll(cardSelector))
if (items.length === 0) return
const activeEl = document.activeElement
if (!container.contains(activeEl)) return
const currentIndex = items.indexOf(activeEl)
if (currentIndex === -1) return
// …
}Every one of those return statements is just an early exit. It doesn’t stop the event, it doesn’t prevent the default action, it just says “nothing more to do here.” And that is fine — in regular code, returning nothing is a normal way to say “nothing found.”
That reminded me of a conversation with my colleague earlier about the same contract: that null often means “nothing found” or “nothing to return.” For example, if you search an array and the element is not there, null is a clean way to say “nothing here” without adding a separate message:
const user = users.find(user => user.id === id)
return user || nullAnd that got me thinking about addEventListener. You can attach a bunch of listeners to the same element:
const button = document.querySelector('button')
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
console.log('first listener')
return false
})
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
console.log('second listener')
})
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
console.log('third listener')
})If the first listener’s return false could stop the event, which listener would win? The DOM sidesteps that by ignoring return values. So why does return false in a Vue event handler do nothing? That is the question this post is about.
What People Expect: The on* Handler Behavior
In classic HTML, you can assign an event handler through an inline onclick attribute or through an element.onclick property. In both cases, the browser treats the return value of that function as a signal.
<form onsubmit="return false;">
<button>Submit</button>
</form>
const link = document.querySelector('a')
link.onclick = function () {
return false
}When a handler assigned this way returns false, the browser interprets that as a request to call event.preventDefault() and, in some cases, event.stopPropagation(). The effect is not magic; it is a special rule in the HTML specification for event handlers that are tied directly to an element via on* properties. The same mechanism applies to inline onclick, onsubmit, onkeydown, and so on.
If you are used to this behavior, it is natural to expect Vue to do the same. After all, both let you attach a function to a DOM event. But Vue does not use onclick. It uses addEventListener, and addEventListener does not look at the return value of the callback at all.
Why addEventListener Ignores Return Values
The addEventListener API is the standard way to attach event listeners in modern JavaScript. Multiple listeners can be registered on the same event, the same element, and the same phase. This is one of its main advantages over on* handlers, which only allow one handler per event.
const button = document.querySelector('button')
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
console.log('first listener')
return false
})
button.addEventListener('click', () => {
console.log('second listener')
})The return false in the first listener does nothing. The second listener still runs, and the default behavior still occurs. This is by design.
If addEventListener were to interpret a return value of false as a signal to prevent the default behavior, it would run into a problem. Which listener’s return value should win? If one listener returns false and another returns true, the browser would need a rule to decide whether to prevent the default. That would be ambiguous and fragile. The DOM Events specification avoids this by simply saying that addEventListener callbacks do not have a return value with any effect.
The return value is also not useful for stopping propagation. stopPropagation is a method call on the event object, not a return value. Because addEventListener supports multiple listeners and was designed to be composable, the only reliable ways to control the event are through explicit calls on the event object:
button.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
event.preventDefault() // cancel the default action
event.stopPropagation() // stop the event from bubbling further
})This is the model that Vue follows. Vue uses addEventListener internally, so the return value of your handler is not inspected for side effects. return false is treated as an ordinary return value: it is ignored.
How Vue Handles Events
Vue’s v-on directive (or the @ shorthand) binds your handler to a wrapper function. That wrapper is the actual function passed to addEventListener.
When you write:
<template>
<button @click="handleClick">Click me</button>
</template>
<script setup>
function handleClick(event) {
console.log('clicked')
}
</script>Vue roughly creates a function that looks like this:

function createInvoker(initialValue, instance) {
const invoker = (e) => {
const value = invoker.value
if (isArray(value)) {
const originalStop = e.stopImmediatePropagation
e.stopImmediatePropagation = () => {
originalStop.call(e)
e._stopped = true
}
const handlers = value.slice()
const args = [e]
for (let i = 0; i < handlers.length; i++) {
if (e._stopped) {
break
}
const handler = handlers[i]
if (handler) {
callWithAsyncErrorHandling(
handler,
instance,
ErrorCodes.NATIVE_EVENT_HANDLER,
args,
)
}
}
} else {
callWithAsyncErrorHandling(
value,
instance,
ErrorCodes.NATIVE_EVENT_HANDLER,
[e],
)
}
}
invoker.value = initialValue
return invoker
}The actual version imports isArray from @vue/shared and also handles timestamp checks; this is trimmed here for clarity. The key point is that the return value of callWithAsyncErrorHandling is not checked for false or true or any other value. The wrapper does not call event.preventDefault() or event.stopPropagation() based on the result.
This is why return false does nothing in a Vue event handler. The function is called, but its return value is not used to control the event.
Why Not Make return false Work Like jQuery?
Some people coming from jQuery expect return false in an event handler to call both preventDefault() and stopPropagation(). jQuery explicitly redefined this behavior for its own event system, but Vue does not.
There is a good reason for this. Vue tries to stay close to the native DOM API. If Vue treated return false specially, it would create a custom behavior that would surprise developers who understand how addEventListener works. It would also make code harder to reason about, because return false would mean something different in Vue than it does in native JavaScript.
This design was discussed early in Vue’s history. In 2014, someone opened an issue asking whether Vue’s v-on should treat return false like jQuery. The issue was opened and closed the same day. Evan You, Vue’s creator, replied directly, explaining that v-on passes the handler’s return value straight through to the raw event listener so the result stays consistent with native browser behavior — your handler gets wrapped in another function, and that wrapper simply returns whatever your handler returned, nothing more. Asked why bother passing it through at all, he was direct about the reasoning: he wanted Vue’s behavior to match the native platform rather than jQuery’s conventions, since “not everyone expects Vue to work like jQuery.”
You can read the full discussion in vuejs/Discussion#44.
Taken together, these comments explain the policy. Vue is not trying to be jQuery. It is trying to match the native event model. Because addEventListener ignores return values, Vue ignores return values too.
The Exception: Vue’s Event Modifiers
There is one place where Vue does allow a declarative way to prevent the default or stop propagation: template modifiers.
<template>
<a href="https://example.com" @click.prevent="handleClick">Go</a>
</template>Vue compiles this into a wrapper that calls event.preventDefault() before invoking your handler. It is not because the handler returns false. It is because the compiler generated the explicit call for you.
The full compiled output looks something like this:
function($event) {
$event.preventDefault()
return handleClick($event)
}The .stop modifier works the same way, but it calls event.stopPropagation() instead:
<template>
<div @click.stop="handleClick">Click</div>
</template>And you can chain them:
<template>
<a href="https://example.com" @click.prevent.stop="handleClick">Go</a>
</template>These modifiers are a convenience. They are compiled to the exact native calls you would write manually. They are not a special interpretation of return false.
Modifier or manual call — does it matter which you use?
Functionally, no. You’ve got two equivalent paths to the same result, and the only real difference is where the calls live.
Use the modifier when you want the template to own the side effect:
<a href="/" @click.prevent="goHome">Go home</a>Use the manual call when the decision needs to live inside the handler logic:
<script setup>
function handleSubmit(event) {
if (invalid) {
event.preventDefault()
return
}
submitForm()
}
</script>Both produce the same native behavior. Vue is not introducing a new layer of meaning around return false. It is simply exposing the existing event.preventDefault() and event.stopPropagation() APIs either through the template or through the handler.
A Note About Vue 2
In Vue 2, the compiler also generated wrapper functions for modifiers, but there was an interesting quirk. A PR in 2018, vuejs/vue#7704, fixed the generated code so that the wrapper function returned the result of the user’s handler.
Without the fix, the compiler would generate something like:
on: {
click: function($event) {
$event.preventDefault()
_vm.test($event) // no return
}
}After the fix, the compiler generated:
on: {
click: function($event) {
$event.preventDefault()
return _vm.test($event)
}
}This was important for consistency, because it meant that code calling the handler function directly could still see the return value. But even with this fix, Vue does not use the return value for preventDefault or stopPropagation. The return is just there to pass the value through.
The Short Version

• Vue attaches event handlers using addEventListener, not legacy on* properties.

• addEventListener ignores the return value of its callbacks, so return false does nothing.

• This matches the native DOM model, where the only way to prevent the default or stop propagation is to call event.preventDefault() or event.stopPropagation().

• Vue gives you .prevent and .stop modifiers as a shortcut, but those are compiled to explicit native calls, not a special interpretation of return false.

• return false in Vue has no effect because the event model it is built on has no effect for return false.
If you want to control an event in Vue, be explicit. Use .prevent, .stop, or the event object. return false is a habit that comes from a different API, and in
